Here is a cleaner documentation text you can use:

```markdown
# Cameras

## Simulation

The simulated camera setup is used as the reference layout. The real robot cameras should match the same logical names: `front`, `rear`, `left`, and `right`.

## Real Robot

The real robot uses four USB cameras connected to the Jetson. The front and rear cameras were adjusted to have a similar orientation to the simulated cameras, but with a slightly different angle to improve ArUco marker visibility. Because of this, there may be small differences between the real robot and the simulation.

## Identifying Cameras

Before running the camera nodes, identify which physical camera corresponds to each `/dev/video*` device.

Run:

```bash
cd ~/gr4_ws
source /opt/ros/humble/setup.bash
source install/setup.bash
ros2 run gr4_camera_config identify_cameras
```

The script lists all visible video devices and saves labeled snapshots in:

```bash
~/gr4_ws/camera_identification/
```

Only the `video-index0` devices can normally capture images. The `video-index1` devices may appear, but usually cannot be opened by OpenCV.

After checking the saved images, the current camera mapping is:

| Snapshot | Physical camera | Stable USB path |
|---|---|---|
| `video0.jpg` | left camera | `platform-3610000.usb-usb-0:2.4.4.1:1.0-video-index0` |
| `video2.jpg` | right camera | `platform-3610000.usb-usb-0:2.4.4.2:1.0-video-index0` |
| `video4.jpg` | rear camera | `platform-3610000.usb-usb-0:2.4.4.3:1.0-video-index0` |
| `video6.jpg` | front camera | `platform-3610000.usb-usb-0:2.4.4.4:1.0-video-index0` |

The mapping is stored in:

```bash
src/gr4_camera_config/config/camera_mapping.yaml
```

The runtime camera node also contains the same mapping in:

```bash
src/gr4_camera_config/gr4_camera_config/physical_four_camera_node.py
```

If USB cables or hub ports are changed, rerun `identify_cameras` and update the mapping if needed.
```
